WEBVTT

00:08.000 --> 00:12.542
(FILM CREW CLAMORING)

00:12.625 --> 00:15.125
-CREW 1: Jess, it's this way.
-JESSICA CHASTAIN: Oh, sorry.

00:16.417 --> 00:18.500
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

00:18.583 --> 00:20.291
CREW 1: What time
are you thinking for lunch?

00:20.375 --> 00:22.667
-JESSICA: Uh, one, maybe?
-CREW 1: Okay.

00:22.750 --> 00:24.166
CREW 2: Hey.

00:27.375 --> 00:28.500
JESSICA: Yeah?

00:28.583 --> 00:30.375
CREW 2: Yeah, I know,
it looks just great. Love it.

00:30.458 --> 00:33.333
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

00:38.542 --> 00:40.375
JESSICA: Hey.
Here you go. Thanks.

00:41.417 --> 00:44.375
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

00:48.500 --> 00:49.625
Hi. Thanks.

00:49.709 --> 00:51.125
You're welcome.

00:54.583 --> 00:56.709
DIRECTOR:
Quiet, please, everyone. Hey.

00:56.792 --> 00:58.959
-Standby to roll, guys.
-JESSICA: Okay.

00:59.041 --> 01:00.208
(BELL RINGS)

01:00.291 --> 01:02.000
CREW 4: Okay. That's it.

01:02.083 --> 01:03.625
DIRECTOR: Let's get slate in.

01:04.625 --> 01:05.583
Here you go.

01:05.667 --> 01:07.583
DIRECTOR: And action!

01:07.667 --> 01:09.500
(SILENCE)

01:10.917 --> 01:14.375
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

01:16.834 --> 01:18.166
(MESSAGE SENT)

01:19.709 --> 01:21.667
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

02:05.834 --> 02:08.875
(JONATHAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

02:08.959 --> 02:11.583
JESSICA: Hey, I'm just gonna
check on her.

02:11.667 --> 02:14.250
WALLACE: (ON IPAD) I've never
seen anything like it!

02:15.583 --> 02:17.500
Heavens above, Gromit!

02:17.583 --> 02:20.625
(SIGHS) Hi. I'm--
I'm Mira. It's nice to meet you.

02:20.709 --> 02:22.417
DANIELLE: Nice to meet you too.
I'm Danielle.

02:22.500 --> 02:24.625
-JONATHAN LEVY: Everything okay?
-MIRA LEVY: Mm-hmm.

02:24.709 --> 02:26.583
DANIELLE: Should we get started?

02:27.250 --> 02:28.458
Yeah.

02:29.458 --> 02:31.375
(BIRDS SINGING)

02:31.458 --> 02:32.750
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

02:36.875 --> 02:38.625
DANIELLE: So, Mira.

02:38.709 --> 02:41.208
I don't know if you remember me
from drop-off?

02:41.291 --> 02:43.417
I babysit Iris and Sadie.

02:43.500 --> 02:45.041
-MIRA: Oh, um...
-DANIELLE: Yeah.

02:45.125 --> 02:47.375
-MIRA: I'm not sure, I-- right.
-DANIELLE: Yeah. So, um...

02:47.458 --> 02:49.041
Well, I believe
Jonathan told you

02:49.125 --> 02:50.917
a bit about my study,
in general?

02:51.000 --> 02:54.583
-MIRA: Um...
-DANIELLE: Well, it's for my PhD
in Gender Studies and Psych

02:54.667 --> 02:55.917
-at Tufts.
-MIRA: Oh, okay.

02:56.000 --> 02:58.500
DANIELLE: I'm looking at how
evolving gender norms

02:58.583 --> 03:00.667
-affect monogamous marriages.
-MIRA: Okay.

03:01.333 --> 03:02.625
DANIELLE: Okay. Um...

03:02.709 --> 03:05.834
So, to complete the formalities,
just confirming your pronouns?

03:06.709 --> 03:08.125
He, him, his.

03:11.041 --> 03:13.917
-She, um--
-She, her, hers.

03:14.959 --> 03:17.709
DANIELLE: Great.
Mine are she/her, too.

03:17.792 --> 03:20.542
-(PAPER RUSTLING)
-Um... okay.

03:20.625 --> 03:21.917
So, yeah.

03:22.000 --> 03:24.583
The first question
is pretty open,

03:24.667 --> 03:26.417
it's for either one of you.

03:26.500 --> 03:28.291
How would you define yourself?

03:30.000 --> 03:31.583
-Define?
-I dunno... (CHUCKLES)

03:31.667 --> 03:33.417
Def-- Like, describe?

03:33.500 --> 03:34.917
-DANIELLE: Well, define.
-Right.

03:35.000 --> 03:37.875
DANIELLE: I'm-- I'm actually
interested in the...

03:39.000 --> 03:40.333
-the elements...
-Mm-hmm.

03:40.417 --> 03:43.000
...that constitute
your self-definition.

03:44.291 --> 03:46.583
The elements that constitute...

03:46.667 --> 03:48.250
-Go first.
-...your self-definition.

03:48.333 --> 03:50.667
That's, um...

03:51.917 --> 03:53.875
DANIELLE: Well,
you could think of it like this.

03:53.959 --> 03:55.750
What, um, attributes

03:55.834 --> 03:58.583
couldn't you imagine
yourself without?

03:58.667 --> 04:00.417
(CHUCKLES) That's interesting.

04:00.500 --> 04:02.125
Uh, okay. Let me think.

04:02.208 --> 04:03.583
DANIELLE:
Actually, if it's okay,

04:03.667 --> 04:05.250
just say whatever comes to mind.

04:05.333 --> 04:07.458
Okay. Uh, I'm a man.

04:07.542 --> 04:09.166
I'm Jewish.

04:09.875 --> 04:11.291
That's weird, right?

04:11.375 --> 04:12.875
-That's so weird.
-That's strange.

04:12.959 --> 04:14.542
I went blank,
that's the first thing

04:14.625 --> 04:16.583
-that came into my head.
-DANIELLE: Great, yes.

04:16.667 --> 04:18.750
-That's exactly the idea.
-Yes. Right. Okay.

04:18.834 --> 04:23.000
-Um, I'm, uh, a father to Ava...
-DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.

04:23.083 --> 04:25.125
...who's four years old,
as you know.

04:25.208 --> 04:28.208
Um... I'm an academic.

04:28.291 --> 04:30.000
Uh, I should've said that first,
actually.

04:30.083 --> 04:31.750
-DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.
-It's a big part of my

04:31.834 --> 04:33.458
-self-definition.
-Mm-hmm.

04:33.542 --> 04:36.375
-I teach in the philosophy
department at Tufts.
-DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.

04:37.667 --> 04:39.125
Um...

04:39.208 --> 04:42.000
What else?
I'm, uh, 41.

04:42.083 --> 04:44.917
-I'm a Democrat.
-Yeah.

04:45.000 --> 04:46.250
I'm an asthmatic.

04:46.333 --> 04:49.000
Whoa. You feel your asthma
defines you?

04:49.083 --> 04:50.834
-Yeah.
-Really?

04:50.917 --> 04:52.917
Yeah. Well, if you go through
your whole life

04:53.000 --> 04:55.333
threatened with the possibility
of suffocating, then yeah,

04:55.417 --> 04:58.959
you know, it becomes part
of your self-definition.

04:59.041 --> 05:00.166
-Okay.
-What?

05:00.250 --> 05:03.250
No. Nothing, babe.
It's-- it's interesting.

05:03.333 --> 05:04.291
-Really.
-Is it?

05:04.375 --> 05:05.667
-Yes.
-Okay.

05:05.750 --> 05:07.083
-(LAUGHS)
-Cool.

05:08.583 --> 05:10.917
DANIELLE: And Mira,
how would you...

05:11.542 --> 05:13.333
Right. I-- Okay. Me.

05:13.417 --> 05:15.125
I am a woman.

05:15.208 --> 05:17.000
-I'm married.
-Correct.

05:17.083 --> 05:18.583
I am a mother.

05:18.667 --> 05:20.500
-Mm-hmm.
-I am 40.

05:20.583 --> 05:22.709
I-- Not quite,
but that's definitely

05:22.792 --> 05:24.667
-my self-definition, 40.
-(LAUGHS)

05:24.750 --> 05:28.208
I'm, uh... in tech.

05:28.291 --> 05:32.792
I'm, uh, VP of
product management at Horizon.

05:32.875 --> 05:35.583
I know that doesn't mean much
to most people,

05:35.667 --> 05:37.208
-but, you know--
-She's a big shot.

05:37.291 --> 05:38.458
-Trust me.
-Yeah--

05:40.166 --> 05:42.750
Um, okay, what else? (SIGHS)

05:43.500 --> 05:45.208
I'm a mother, obviously.

05:45.291 --> 05:47.500
You said that, don't worry.

05:47.583 --> 05:49.500
-Oh, good.
-(CHUCKLES)

05:52.959 --> 05:54.166
Is that enough?

05:55.583 --> 05:56.959
Um...

05:57.041 --> 05:59.291
unless there's anything else
you'd like to add?

05:59.375 --> 06:01.917
-MIRA: Oh, no. I'm good.
-JONATHAN: Yeah.

06:02.000 --> 06:05.041
I wonder, for instance,
if you'd like to add something

06:05.125 --> 06:06.417
um, about how you divide

06:06.500 --> 06:08.250
household and caregiving
responsibilities...

06:08.333 --> 06:10.875
-Right. Yes. Um...
-DANIELLE: ...in that context?

06:11.000 --> 06:12.917
So, I forgot to mention
she's interested in couples

06:13.000 --> 06:14.917
where the woman
is the primary provider.

06:15.000 --> 06:17.083
-DANIELLE: Yeah. Well, um...
-Oh.

06:17.166 --> 06:19.333
-Right? Is that--
-DANIELLE: Yeah,
I wouldn't exactly...

06:19.417 --> 06:20.750
-put it that way, but it's--
-Oh, yes. Sorry.

06:20.834 --> 06:22.917
I'm not-- I'm not-- I'm not
trying to give away your thesis.

06:23.000 --> 06:24.041
DANIELLE: That's... that's fine.

06:24.125 --> 06:25.875
Uh, anyway, yes.
So, for the most part,

06:25.959 --> 06:27.625
I do take care of Ava
during the week.

06:27.709 --> 06:29.166
-Um...
-Well, uh...

06:30.000 --> 06:32.959
Well, being in academia,
as you know,

06:33.041 --> 06:36.750
I have very flexible hours
and I can work from home.

06:36.834 --> 06:38.750
Mira, she works long days and...

06:38.834 --> 06:41.458
-has to travel for work.
-And I make it up to them
on the weekends.

06:41.542 --> 06:43.834
-Yeah, and you make it home
for bedtime, when you can.
-Yeah.

06:43.917 --> 06:45.417
DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.

06:45.500 --> 06:48.291
And has this always been
your arrangement,
in terms of childcare?

06:48.375 --> 06:49.917
-Yeah, pretty much.
-Well, yeah. I had--

06:50.000 --> 06:51.250
Well, I had to take

06:51.333 --> 06:53.458
-an extra-long maternity leave.
-Yes.

06:53.542 --> 06:56.166
And, um, you know,
I'm still paying for it at work.

06:56.250 --> 06:57.250
Of course. Yeah.

06:57.333 --> 06:59.250
And my company is going public
later this year,

06:59.333 --> 07:01.709
-so that's why there's
so much extra travel.
-Yeah, and it's also, like,

07:01.792 --> 07:03.875
I'm not making a big, uh,
heroic sacrifice or anything.

07:03.959 --> 07:05.792
-No. (CHUCKLES)
-We have our babysitter,
Veronica,

07:05.875 --> 07:08.208
and she does extra hours,
uh, on the, you know,

07:08.291 --> 07:10.041
on the days
that I'm underwater at work.

07:10.125 --> 07:12.208
-DANIELLE: Sure.
-And look, it'd be great

07:12.291 --> 07:15.333
if academia paid
as well as tech does,

07:15.417 --> 07:16.959
-but it doesn't...
-It doesn't, no.

07:17.041 --> 07:19.500
...so this arrangement
makes perfect sense.

07:19.583 --> 07:21.166
-Yeah.
-DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.

07:21.250 --> 07:24.041
It sounds like
we're apologizing for it. Maybe.

07:24.125 --> 07:26.625
-DANIELLE: No, not at all.
-Yeah. No, we're proud of it.

07:26.709 --> 07:28.875
-(CHUCKLES)
-Babe. Don't.

07:32.166 --> 07:36.500
Okay. So, at this point,
I'd like to...

07:36.583 --> 07:38.291
hear a little bit
about your history.

07:38.375 --> 07:41.166
I know that you've been married
for almost ten years.

07:41.250 --> 07:42.125
JONATHAN: Yes.

07:42.208 --> 07:44.583
How long were you together
before that?

07:44.667 --> 07:46.333
It's like two years and change,
maybe?

07:46.417 --> 07:48.291
-Mm-hmm. Yeah.
-Twelve years total.

07:48.375 --> 07:50.417
-Mm-hmm.
-DANIELLE: And how did you meet?

07:52.583 --> 07:54.208
-You should be the one
to tell the story.
-No.

07:54.291 --> 07:55.959
It's way more entertaining.
Come on.

07:56.041 --> 07:58.041
(SIGHS)

07:58.125 --> 08:01.417
Is-- Can you tell me
how this is part of the study?

08:02.250 --> 08:04.500
DANIELLE:
Um, well, it's valuable

08:04.583 --> 08:07.375
in the context
of the gender perceptions

08:07.458 --> 08:09.959
you had at the beginning
of the relationship.

08:10.041 --> 08:12.041
Okay. I just-- I've...

08:12.125 --> 08:14.125
I was under the impression
that this is gonna be

08:14.208 --> 08:16.291
more like multiple choice.

08:16.959 --> 08:18.583
DANIELLE: Sorry, no.

08:19.208 --> 08:20.458
Okay.

08:21.583 --> 08:24.500
I'll tell it. It's actually--
It's a good story.

08:24.583 --> 08:25.875
-And, uh...
-Mm-hmm.

08:25.959 --> 08:27.959
You can just interject
when I get melodramatic.

08:28.041 --> 08:29.125
Sure.

08:30.417 --> 08:32.208
So, we met at Columbia.

08:32.291 --> 08:35.166
Um, we went there,
we were in a seminar together,

08:35.250 --> 08:36.709
English lit.

08:36.792 --> 08:42.291
So, um, we spent three hours
a week in a tiny little room,

08:42.375 --> 08:44.250
uh, but at this point,
there was no way

08:44.333 --> 08:46.041
-that we would have ever...
-No.

08:46.125 --> 08:48.667
I should mention that I was
still Orthodox at the time.

08:48.750 --> 08:50.500
-DANIELLE: Oh?
-Yeah. Yes.

08:50.583 --> 08:52.750
I, uh, I grew up
in a Modern Orthodox

08:52.834 --> 08:54.125
-Jewish family.
-Mm-hmm.

08:54.208 --> 08:57.417
So up until that point,
up until college, my education

08:57.500 --> 09:00.750
had been mostly single-sex,
I'd never touched a woman.

09:00.834 --> 09:05.083
So the whole thing
was pretty overwhelming,

09:05.166 --> 09:09.917
um, me with my black yarmulke
and white button-down shirts,

09:10.000 --> 09:13.583
and all these young women
in their little tank tops.

09:13.667 --> 09:16.375
And Mira specifically
was like a campus celebrity.

09:16.458 --> 09:19.583
She was dating a member
of a big rock band at the time,

09:19.667 --> 09:21.250
that needless to say
I'd never heard of.

09:21.333 --> 09:23.417
No, they were--
they weren't really rock,

09:23.500 --> 09:24.625
and they weren't big.

09:24.709 --> 09:26.792
You've probably heard of them,
Saraband? Lucas McRae?

09:26.875 --> 09:28.250
-Oh, wow.
-JONATHAN: Uh, yeah.

09:28.333 --> 09:30.750
I just thought-- I thought
of Mira as kind of a...

09:30.834 --> 09:32.250
-A what?
-No, no, no.

09:32.333 --> 09:34.417
-No. Tell me. I wanna--
-Yeah, it-- it--

09:34.500 --> 09:37.375
it's just that you were
as far away from my world

09:37.458 --> 09:39.417
as it-- as it got, you know.

09:39.500 --> 09:42.458
And anyway, I was already
engaged to a girl

09:42.542 --> 09:46.041
that I grew up with
near Long Island.

09:46.125 --> 09:47.792
-DANIELLE: Oh.
-Yeah.

09:47.875 --> 09:52.291
-So how did it happen?
-JONATHAN: (CHUCKLES)
Uh, well, she just...

09:52.375 --> 09:55.667
just walked up to me one day
and, um...

09:56.333 --> 09:57.709
This part you should tell.

09:58.500 --> 10:02.792
Um, okay. So I was in a, um...

10:02.875 --> 10:04.208
a theater group in school,

10:04.291 --> 10:06.917
and we were doing this one play
by Bashevis Singer, and--

10:07.000 --> 10:10.125
An adaptation of
Enemies, A Love Story.

10:10.208 --> 10:11.458
-Hmm.
-MIRA: Right.

10:11.542 --> 10:15.041
And, um, so I was doing all
this research on Orthodox Jews.

10:15.125 --> 10:17.458
I was very serious about acting
in college.

10:17.542 --> 10:19.458
-Oh, yeah.
-And so I just went up to him

10:19.542 --> 10:21.667
one day after class, and I asked
if I could talk to him,

10:21.750 --> 10:24.709
-and he just-- he seemed
completely horrified--
-I was, yeah, paralyzed.

10:24.792 --> 10:27.500
MIRA: Yeah. But I was
very committed to this role.

10:27.583 --> 10:28.542
JONATHAN: Absolutely.

10:28.625 --> 10:30.667
So committed
that she got completely naked

10:30.750 --> 10:32.875
-halfway through the play.
-MIRA: No! Not completely.

10:32.959 --> 10:35.875
And I'd already started
the process

10:35.959 --> 10:37.750
of, uh, leaving my religion.

10:38.709 --> 10:40.917
But, uh, no, that-- that--

10:41.000 --> 10:42.709
that show was
definitely a milestone.

10:42.792 --> 10:45.375
Mm. You mean
you actually started dating?

10:45.458 --> 10:47.709
MIRA: Oh, no, no, no, no.
Not until years later.

10:47.792 --> 10:49.542
JONATHAN: Yeah. Yeah,
I was already here in Boston,

10:49.625 --> 10:51.166
and I was, uh,

10:51.250 --> 10:53.208
...creeping around
on her Myspace page,

10:53.291 --> 10:55.625
and I saw
that she was moving here

10:55.709 --> 10:58.166
and that she was looking
for an apartment share.

10:58.250 --> 10:59.834
So we became roommates.

10:59.917 --> 11:01.917
And from there, it progressed.

11:04.000 --> 11:05.625
DANIELLE:
And who initiated that?

11:09.458 --> 11:11.083
JONATHAN:
I think it was both of us?

11:12.041 --> 11:13.959
-Yeah.
-Right?

11:14.583 --> 11:15.750
Yeah.

11:16.667 --> 11:18.750
-Both.
-(CHUCKLES)

11:20.041 --> 11:23.083
I had just come out of a series
of relationships

11:23.166 --> 11:24.291
which were...

11:24.959 --> 11:26.375
borderline abusive.

11:26.458 --> 11:30.959
And I guess
that I was addicted to that,

11:31.041 --> 11:32.166
and I-- and I was...

11:35.458 --> 11:36.667
stuck.

11:36.750 --> 11:40.125
Uh, I had a job that I could
care less about.

11:40.208 --> 11:41.875
DANIELLE: Mm.

11:41.959 --> 11:45.709
And Jonathan
was the complete opposite.

11:45.792 --> 11:48.875
Uh, he was everything
that I wanted to be.

11:49.875 --> 11:52.291
He had values, and purpose.

11:52.375 --> 11:55.166
-It's true.
-Yeah, well. Yeah, I...

11:56.208 --> 11:57.208
It's ironic because this was

11:57.291 --> 12:00.500
at the height of my
existential dread.

12:00.583 --> 12:02.333
After I left my religion,

12:02.417 --> 12:06.333
I just had these years
of loneliness and... (CHUCKLES)

12:07.667 --> 12:10.834
So... when did it happen?

12:12.750 --> 12:15.542
MIRA: Well, it happened...

12:15.625 --> 12:18.417
-thanks to the asthma, actually.
-(CHUCKLES)

12:18.500 --> 12:19.792
DANIELLE: The asthma?

12:19.875 --> 12:23.834
Yeah. There was this one time
we were coming back from the ER,

12:23.917 --> 12:26.959
I'd had a very severe attack,
and the, um, the doctor...

12:27.041 --> 12:28.083
(CLEARS THROAT)

12:28.166 --> 12:30.417
...he mistook us
for a married couple,

12:30.500 --> 12:33.375
and, uh... we liked it,

12:33.458 --> 12:38.250
and we came home
and we kept playing at it.

12:38.333 --> 12:39.500
And, um...

12:41.041 --> 12:42.959
and then it happened.

12:43.041 --> 12:45.000
DANIELLE: That's great.
That's perfect.

12:45.083 --> 12:47.125
So... All right.

12:47.208 --> 12:49.291
-Now, I'd like to hear...
-(WHISPERING) It's almost over.

12:49.375 --> 12:50.875
...a bit about, in your opinion,

12:50.959 --> 12:54.542
what is the primary factor

12:54.625 --> 12:57.583
contributing to the success
of your marriage?

12:58.333 --> 13:00.583
-Hmm.
-(CHUCKLES)

13:00.667 --> 13:02.834
-Hmm.
-I-- I'll let you take this.

13:02.917 --> 13:04.834
Interesting.
(CHUCKLES) Interesting.

13:04.917 --> 13:07.667
Could you actually tell us what
the definition of success is

13:07.750 --> 13:09.083
that you're working with?

13:09.166 --> 13:11.125
Yeah. Well, uh, first of all,

13:11.208 --> 13:13.291
it means that
you're still together.

13:13.375 --> 13:14.834
-Uh--
-That's a low bar.

13:14.917 --> 13:17.500
(LAUGHS) Yeah. Yeah.

13:17.583 --> 13:21.583
Well, does our ten years
make us statistical outliers?

13:21.667 --> 13:23.542
-DANIELLE: Mm-hmm.
-(CELL PHONE VIBRATES)

13:23.625 --> 13:26.583
DANIELLE: Well, if we ignore
all the socioeconomic

13:26.667 --> 13:28.792
and race parameters, then yes.

